Import-Module ActiveDirectory
Write-Host &ldquo;Tuple Index Enabled Attributes&rdquo;
Get-ADObject -SearchBase ((Get-ADRootDSE).schemaNamingContext) -SearchScope OneLevel -LDAPFilter &ldquo;(searchFlags:1.2.840.113556.1.4.803:=32)&rdquo; -Property objectClass, name, whenChanged, whenCreated, LDAPDisplayNAme | Out-GridView
Write-Host &ldquo;ANR Enabled Attributes&rdquo;
Get-ADObject -SearchBase ((Get-ADRootDSE).schemaNamingContext) -SearchScope OneLevel -LDAPFilter &ldquo;(searchFlags:1.2.840.113556.1.4.803:=4)&rdquo; -Property objectClass, name, whenChanged, whenCreated, LDAPDisplayNAme | Out-GridView
Write-Host &ldquo;Indexed Enabled Attributes&rdquo;
Get-ADObject -SearchBase ((Get-ADRootDSE).schemaNamingContext) -SearchScope OneLevel -LDAPFilter &ldquo;(searchFlags:1.2.840.113556.1.4.803:=1)&rdquo; -Property objectClass, name, whenChanged, whenCreated, LDAPDisplayNAme | Out-GridView
The above script is something I use to quickly look and see what is indexed in an AD environment

Searching an entire database for a Guid or Unique Identifier can be a bit of a tricky proposition. However a little bit of using T-SQL to generate T-SQL and viola
DECLARE @GUIDHunted nvarchar(60)
SET @GUIDHunted = &lsquo;0A24EC0C-65EE-4519-89DF-ABD3DD24F7EF&rsquo;
SELECT *, &lsquo;UNION ALL SELECT &rsquo;&rsquo;&rsquo; + s.name + &lsquo;.&rsquo; + ao.name + &lsquo;&rsquo;&rsquo;, count(*) FROM &rsquo;
+ s.name +&rsquo;.[&rsquo; + ao.name + &lsquo;] WHERE &rsquo; + ac.name + &rsquo; = &rsquo;&rsquo;&rsquo; + @GuidHunted + &rsquo;&rsquo;&rsquo;&rsquo;

Last night as I took my children trick or treating through our neighborhood I thought about Halloween from an Identity Management Perspective:
We provision temporary identities to our children (costumes) that allow them to make a claim when they show up at neighbors&rsquo; doors &ldquo;Trick or Treat (I am wearing costume &ndash; the claim; will your grant me access to candy &ndash; the resource request)?&rdquo;
At which point the neighbor will almost invariably give out some candy.
